def fibonacci(n):
    if n <= 0:
        return "Invalid input. n must be a positive integer."
    elif n == 1:
        return 0
    elif n == 2:
        return 1
    else:
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2)
```

To use this function, you can call it with the desired value of `n`:

```python
result = fibonacci(n)
print(result)
```

Note that this implementation has an exponential time complexity, so it may not be efficient for large values of `n`.
